2026-04-16 12:34:04 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['main lamp in load module'] hypothesis_explanation='Continuity mapping shows correct polarity and low‑resistance paths for both + and – rails across all modules, so the intermittent behavior is not due to mis‑wiring or supply loss. Measured voltage at the load module input is only ~0.36 V on the + lead and ~0 V on the – lead, and this remains constant even when the visible lamp turns off for 0.5 s. That indicates that practically no current is being drawn from the 12 V supply in any state, i.e., the main 12 V loop from battery through supply, sensor module, and load is open. The intermittent darkening of the external lamp while the tiny indicator lamp behavior remains unchanged is most consistent with an internal intermittent open circuit in the main lamp assembly itself (e.g., filament or internal connection that opens and re‑makes every ~20 s). Because the diode, internal wiring, and indicator lamp are in parallel with the main lamp and would keep conducting steadily, an intermittent open in the main lamp alone explains a periodic visible outage while all measured supply conditions and control circuitry remain steady. Therefore the most likely single faulty component is the main lamp in the load module.'
